<p><b>How do philosophy and other sciences relate to each other?</b> Short answer: Science discovers facts about the universe and seeks natural laws to explain them. Philosophy examines (among other questions unrelated to science) the process of seeking, the character of natural laws, and the nature of explanation. It underlies science.</p>
<p><b>What is the relationship between ethics and other disciplines?</b> General ethics presents truths about human acts to derive moral principles, while special ethics applies these principles to different areas of human activity and relations. The document also discusses the relationship between ethics and other fields like logic, psychology, sociology, and education.</p>
<p><b>What is the function of philosophy in relation to studying other academic disciplines?</b> Understanding Other Disciplines: Philosophy is indispensable for our ability to understand other disciplines. Many important questions about a discipline, such as the nature of its concepts and its relation to other disciplines, are philosophical in nature.</p>